<TITLE> UPR calls for 2-year national government after elections </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 11 (bdnews24.com)  The Unity for Political Reform proposed forming a two-year term government of national consensus after the elections, in dialogue with the government, Wednesday. "We have proposed a balance between the power of the president and the prime minister," party coordinator ASM Abdur Rob told reporters after the dialogue. In a seven-point charter of demands the party also asked for trial of trial of war criminals and imposing a ban on political strikes (hartals). "Others include activating a two-room parliament, appointing one female deputy speaker and one deputy speaker from the opposition in the parliament," said Rob. "We have also asked for an amendment to the 1972 constitution." "Apart from demanding the trial of war criminals, we have demanded an investigation as to why they were not tried for so many years." Chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed led the government side in dialogue, with communications adviser Ghulam Quader, law adviser AF Hassan Ariff and commerce adviser Hossain Zillur Rahman. Hossain Zillur said the party had raised an uncommon proposal  appointing a female deputy speaker in the parliament. "An ordinance has been amended, however, to keep the provision of appointing a female vice president in the upazila parishad." On the party's proposal to amend the constitution, the advsier said: "A positive result will come if the constitution is reviewed on the basis of consensus by keeping up the main aim of the constitution." bdnews24.
